Description: This article talks about Cilium, but does so in the context of the CKS exam. We start with a walkthrough of what Cilium is - basically an eBPF module that does networking at the kernel level. It does this as a CNI or network plugin. While this allows it to do networking, it also enables things like observability and service mesh by these same mechanisms. We then step back and look at default Kubernetes networking, which allows any pod to talk to any other pod in the same cluster - a bigger surface then we'd like. So by using Network policies, we can restrict which pods can talk and how. They then use a YAML snip to show what a "deny all inbound" looks like. Then then show what mods are needed to create a broad accept policy. We go through a few more such examples. They then contrast these with using Cilium, which has more selection and more ways to specify the target of an action. They also point out Cilium has a default deny policy. They go through a number of examples here as well. They also show how to enable mutual auth between pods. 
