DateReviewed: 2026-01-17
Description: This article is about a way to explain what Kubernetes is from a very simple perspective. We dive right in, starting with a diagram and a Docker image as a "recipe". Carrying this analogy forward, a Docker container is the "prepared dish", or what you run on a pod. Going on, the Docker registry is a Recipe book or storage, to formulate new prepared dishes. The push action is adding a single recipe to the book. A pull reverses this process, fetching the recipe from the book. The pod, which I mentioned earlier, is a table that can hold one or more dishes. Now the node is a kitchen worker, which actually makes the prepared dish. It works because multiple nodes map to multiple cooks. A cluster is the full kitchen staff, all working together. A namespace is a section of the kitchen, which is responsible for a subset (think desert or starters). Finally Kubernetes is the head chef or kitchen manager, overseeing and making sure everything is running right. Very well done.
BottomLine: Kubernetes described with simple kitchen analogies
